```

**Infinite loop when `b == 0`**

When `b` is zero, `fltflt_div(a, 0)` returns `{0, 0}` due to the explicit `xn = 0.0f` guard in `fltflt_div`. This causes `trunc_q = {0, 0}` and `result = a` (the positive magnitude of the dividend). The correction loop `while (result >= b)` then evaluates `result >= 0.0`, which is always `true` for positive `result`, and since `fltflt_sub(result, {0,0})` leaves `result` unchanged, the loop never terminates.

The same issue exists in the `fltflt_fmod(fltflt, float)` overload (line 622). The fix should guard against `b == 0` before entering the correction loops, returning NaN to match the behaviour of C's `fmod(x, 0)`:

```cpp
// Add before computing q:
if (b.hi == 0.0f && b.lo == 0.0f) {
    return fltflt{std::numeric_limits<float>::quiet_NaN(),
                  std::numeric_limits<float>::quiet_NaN()};
}
```

**Classified worst-tier result beats unclassified good article**

The `compareExtractions` function unconditionally promotes any classified result above any unclassified result:

```typescript
// Only one has classifier — the classified result wins (we trust classifier over guessing)
if (aHasCls !== bHasCls) return aHasCls ? -1 : 1;
```

This means a source classified as `full_page_not_article` (tier 4 — the worst possible outcome) will rank above an unclassified source that may contain a long, complete article. This can happen legitimately: if Diffbot returns an article but does not include `htmlContent` in its response (the `classify && env.CLASSIFIER_ENABLED && va.htmlContent` guard on line 447 silently skips classification when `htmlContent` is absent), `smry-slow` will have no classification, and `smry-fast`'s `full_page_not_article` result would win.

Consider guarding against the worst tier before applying this rule:

```typescript
// Only prefer the classified result if it isn't the worst tier
if (aHasCls !== bHasCls) {
  const clsSide = aHasCls ? a : b;
  const tier = CLASSIFIER_TIER[clsSide.classification!.outcome] ?? 2;
  if (tier < 4) return aHasCls ? -1 : 1; // full_page_not_article loses to unclassified
  return aHasCls ? 1 : -1; // worst-tier loses to unclassified
}
```

**Hook called after conditional return**

`useCachedPromise` on line 74 is called after the early return on line 62, which violates React's [Rules of Hooks](https://react.dev/reference/rules/rules-of-hooks). Hooks must be called unconditionally and in the same order on every render. When `apiKey` or `username` is missing, the hook is never called — and if the user later fills in the preferences (causing a re-render), the number of hook calls changes, which can crash React.

A straightforward fix is to move the hook call above the guard and use `execute: false` to skip the fetch when credentials are missing:

```suggestion
  const { data: collectionsData, isLoading } = useCachedPromise(
    async () => {
      const result = await getCollections();
      return result.data;
    },
    [],
    { execute: !!apiKey && !!username },
  );

  if (!apiKey || !username) {
    return (
      <List>
        <List.EmptyView
          icon={Icon.Key}
          title="API Key and Username Required"
          description="Set your Wallhaven API key and username in extension preferences to access collections."
        />
      </List>
    );
  }
```

**4xx errors are silently retried despite being non-retryable**

The code throws a `new Error(...)` for 4xx responses on line 152–154 **inside the `try` block**, so that error is immediately caught by the `catch (error)` on line 159. The catch block then retries when `attempt < maxRetries` (line 162), meaning every 4xx response will be retried up to `maxRetries` times — directly contradicting the comment "client errors (4xx) are not" retryable and the PR description.

To truly skip retries for 4xx, the error must either be thrown after the loop, or the catch block must inspect the error to distinguish non-retryable failures.

One clean approach is to use a sentinel:

```typescript
class NonRetryableError extends Error {
    constructor(message: string) {
        super(message)
        this.name = 'NonRetryableError'
    }
}

// ...in the loop...
if (!response.ok()) {
    if (response.status() >= 500 && attempt < maxRetries) {
        // retry 5xx
        await this.delay(2000 * Math.pow(2, attempt - 1))
        continue
    }
    if (throwOnError) {
        throw new NonRetryableError(
            `Playwright setup failed for '${setupType}': ${result.error || 'Unknown error'}`
        )
    }
}

// ...in the catch block...
} catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof NonRetryableError) {
        throw error  // never retry 4xx
    }
    lastError = error instanceof Error ? error : new Error(String(error))
    // ...existing retry logic...
}
```

`searchId` leaked when `getSearchResults` throws

`session.DOM.discardSearchResults` is only called in the happy path and the zero-results early-exit (line 586). If `getSearchResults` (line 590) throws an error that escapes the per-node `try/catch`, the `searchId` is never discarded, leaking a CDP search handle.

Wrapping the retrieval and processing in a `try/finally` ensures cleanup regardless of the outcome:

```suggestion
const matched = await session.DOM.getSearchResults({
  searchId: search.searchId,
  fromIndex: 0,
  toIndex: count,
})

const results: DomSearchResult[] = []
const seen = new Set<number>()
try {
  for (const nodeId of matched.nodeIds) {
    try {
      const desc = await session.DOM.describeNode({ nodeId, depth: 0 })
      let node = desc.node
      let resolvedNodeId = nodeId

      // Text/comment nodes: resolve to parent element via JS
      if (node.nodeType !== 1) {
        const resolved = await session.DOM.resolveNode({ nodeId })
        if (!resolved.object.objectId) continue
        const parentResult = await session.Runtime.callFunctionOn({
          objectId: resolved.object.objectId,
          functionDeclaration: 'function() { return this.parentElement; }',
          returnByValue: false,
        })
        if (!parentResult.result.objectId) continue
        const parentNode = await session.DOM.requestNode({
          objectId: parentResult.result.objectId,
        })
        resolvedNodeId = parentNode.nodeId
        const parentDesc = await session.DOM.describeNode({
          nodeId: parentNode.nodeId,
          depth: 0,
        })
        node = parentDesc.node
      }

      if (node.nodeType !== 1) continue
      if (seen.has(node.backendNodeId)) continue
      seen.add(node.backendNodeId)

      results.push({
        tag: node.localName,
        nodeId: resolvedNodeId,
        backendNodeId: node.backendNodeId,
        attributes: parseNodeAttributes(node),
      })
    } catch {
      // node may have been removed between search and describe
    }
  }
} finally {
  await session.DOM.discardSearchResults({ searchId: search.searchId })
}
return { results, totalCount: search.resultCount }
```

